The tethered fly assay 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olfactory stimuli can be decomposed into a few basic features, like the
 chemical identity of the odorants in the odor, their concentration, and
 the kinetics of the stimulus.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acfp{ORN}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 appear to be able to capture all these features.
 The chemical identity of the odorant is captured by which olfactory neurons
 respond, since different neurons have different receptors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2004ds,Hallem:2004ht"

\end_inset

.
 The concentration of the odorants in the stimulus is captured in part by
 the amplitude of neuronal response 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBruyne:1999uh,deBruyne:2001ur"

\end_inset

, and also by the identity of the neurons that respond, since different
 receptors have different sensitivities to the same odorant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2004ds,Hallem:2004ht"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, the temporal structure of the odorant stimulus is encoded in the
 response kinetics of neuron response 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martelli:2013it"

\end_inset

.
 Insects on the wing can encounter odorant stimuli with varying concentrations
 and durations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Celani:2014ea,vanBreugel:2014is"

\end_inset

, and it is not clear if flies use all these features of the stimulus equally
 to make navigational decisions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{TFA}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, originally developed to study insect flight 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gotz:1968vx"

\end_inset

 was later adapted and modified to study vision, mechanosensation, and the
 visual control of flight 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lehmann:1997vz,Frye:2001ev,Sherman:2003tg,Bender:2006wl,Budick:2007gx"

\end_inset

.
 Recently, the TFA has also been used to study olfaction, either in the
 fixed tethered configuration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bhandawat:2010eu"

\end_inset

 or in rotatable tethered configuration, where flies can actively reorient
 into or away from an odorized airstream 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Frye:2003da,Frye:2004gj,Krishnan:2011eb"

\end_inset

.
 Since the fly is fixed in place in this assay, this makes it possible to
 deliver and measure olfactory stimuli and permits measuring how these olfactory
 stimuli modulate olfactory flight behavior.
 In this assay, the behavior of the fly is quantified by changes in the
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{WBA}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and by changes in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{WBF}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, both of which are measured in real time by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Wing Beat Analyzer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is part of the assay.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next section, I detail my attempts to use this assay to determine
 how flies change their flight behavior with the identity, amplitude and
 duration of olfactory stimuli.
 
