\begin_layout Subsection
A tale of diminishing responses 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do flies respond to pulses of odorant delivered with this new olfactometer?
 I delivered 200 ms pulses of ethyl acetate using this olfactometer to flies
 and measured their WBA and WBF response.
 Odorant pulses still elicited increases in the WBF, but the amplitude of
 responses was much smaller compared to those elicited by pulses delivered
 using the earlier design (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-results-2"

\end_inset

a).
 While pulses of ethyl acetate elicited a complex response in the WBA, comprisin
g of transient responses followed by a slow increase, equivalent pulses
 from the new olfactometer elicited a cleaner WBA response comprising mainly
 of a slow decrease (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tfa-results-2"

\end_inset

a).
 On examining the WBA responses more closely, I observed two peaks in the
 WBA response that occurred 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim40$
\end_inset

ms after valve opening and closing, in both the control and odorant pulse
 responses.
 The fact that these peaks occurred so quickly after valve movement, and
 the fact that they existed in both responses to control pulses and odorant
 pulses, suggested that these peaks corresponded to a mechanical artifact
 associated with the motion of the valve.
 
\end_layout

