\begin_layout Section
Conclusion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flight of flies is a complex behavior, and depends on the integration
 of sensory cues from many modalities, including vision
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Frye:2004gj,Maimon:2010jy,Muijres:2014km"

\end_inset

, mechanosensation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Budick:2007gx"

\end_inset

 and olfaction
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Frye:2004gj,Krishnan:2011eb"

\end_inset

.
 In this assay I attempted to unravel how various features of stimuli of
 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 modality, olfaction, affect the response of flies.
 This task was made even more challenging by the fact that flies rely heavily
 on vision and mechanosensation during flight
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Maimon:2010jy,Muijres:2014km,Muijres:2015ku,Reiser:2013jt,Sherman:2003tg,Tammero:2002wd"

\end_inset

.
 In order to study how olfactory cues modulated flight behavior, olfactory
 cues had to be introduced without introducing other cues, which is a very
 hard problem.
 Since all olfactory cues need to be transported by moving airstreams, deliverin
g any olfactory cue typically relies on valves that switches airstreams.
 Earlier studies have shown that turning valves on and off introduces large,
 transient fluctuations in the airspeed that occur on timescales as fast
 as a few milliseconds
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Daly:2013ij"

\end_inset

.
 The ability of the fly to detect mechanical disturbances in airstreams
 exceeded that of instruments at my disposal, making it hard to know with
 certainty if responses observed here were not contaminated by mechanical
 stimuli originating from valve switching.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further challenge in this work was that flies did not fly reliably in
 this assay.
 Compared to published studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bender:2006wl,Bhandawat:2010eu"

\end_inset

, I observed that flies flew at lower WBFs.
 Flies also tended to stop flying intermittently, making data collection
 arduous.
 The reasons for the poor flight ability of the flies tested here is not
 known, but it could be due to (i) the fact that these experiments were
 conducted in the dark, which is an atypical flying environment for flies,
 and (ii) the genetic background of the flies tested in this study.
 
\end_layout

